{{Infobox person |name = Fredrik Neij |image = Fredrik-neij-portrait.jpg |caption = |birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1978|04|27|df=y}} |birth_place = |birth_name = Hans Fredrik Lennart Neij |death_place = |other_names = TiAMO |known_for = Co-founder of [[The Pirate Bay]] who was convicted of copyright infringement |nationality = Swedish }} '''Hans Fredrik Lennart Neij''' (born 27 April 1978) alias '''TiAMO'''<ref name = "Nation"/> is the co-founder of [[The Pirate Bay]], and the [[Sweden|Swedish]] [[Internet service provider]] and [[web hosting]] company [[PRQ]].<ref>Häyhtiö, Tapio. ''Net working/Networking'', Tampere University Press, p. 344, 2008.</ref> Neij was one of the defendants in [[The Pirate Bay Trial]] which began on 16 February 2009. He and other operators of The Pirate Bay were charged with assisting users in [[copyright infringement|copyright infringing practices]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wired.com/2008/01/pirate-bay-futu/ |title=Pirate Bay Future Uncertain After Operators Busted |last1=Kravets |first1=David|date=2008-01-31 |website=[[Wired (website)|Wired]] |publisher= |access-date=2015-05-29}}</ref> His time during the aforementioned trial has been captured in the documentary film [[TPB AFK]] by [[Simon Klose]].
== Legal Issues ==
On 17 April 2009, Neij was found guilty. He was sentenced to one year in prison and ordered to pay damages of $905,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://torrentfreak.com/the-pirate-bay-trial-the-verdict-090417/|title=The Pirate Bay Trial: The Official Verdict - Guilty - TorrentFreak|work=TorrentFreak|accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref>
In November 2014, Neij was arrested in [[Nong Khai]] on an [[Interpol]] warrant while attempting to cross the border from Laos to [[Thailand]].<ref name = "Nation">{{cite web|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/national/The-Pirate-Bay-co-founder-arrested-in-Nong-Khai-30246926.html|title=The Pirate Bay co-founder arrested in Nong Khai|date=4 November 2014|work=The Nation|accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref><ref name = "TorrentFreak2">{{cite web|url=http://torrentfreak.com/pirate-bay-founder-fredrik-neij-arrested-in-asia-141104/|title=Updated: Pirate Bay Founder Fredrik Neij Arrested in Asia|work=TorrentFreak|accessdate=16 March 2015}}</ref> Thai authorities stated that a US-based film association had a Thai lawyer search for Neij and aid in his capture. During his three years in Laos, he had reportedly crossed the border almost 30 times into Thailand, where he had a home on the resort island of [[Phuket]].<ref name=guar>{{cite news|last1=Press|first1=Associated|title=Pirate Bay co-founder arrested in Thailand|url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2014/nov/04/pirate-bay-founder-fredrik-neij-arrested-thailand|accessdate=13 May 2015|work=the Guardian|date=November 4, 2014}}</ref> [[BayFiles]], a Pirate Bay-affiliated [[file hosting]] website registered under Neij's name, was abruptly shut down after the arrest.<ref name=tff>{{cite web|title=Pirate Bay Cyberlocker Bayfiles Disappears After Arrest|url=https://torrentfreak.com/pirate-bay-founders-file-hosting-site-disappears-141128/|website=Torrentfreak|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref>
Neij served two thirds (200 days) of a 10 months sentence in Skänninge Prison in central [[Sweden]].<ref name="tff" /><ref name=nes>{{cite web|last1=Hay Newman|first1=Lily|title=Pirate Bay Co-Founder Cruelly Held in Swedish Prison Without Classic Nintendo|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/future_tense/2015/04/17/swedish_prison_denies_fredrik_neij_or_tiamo_access_to_his_original_nintendo.html|website=Slate|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> He was released on 1 June 2015 and is planning to settle in Laos and work with [[Information technology|IT]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.com/tech-policy/2015/06/pirate-bay-fredrik-neij-co-founder-released-from-prison/|title=Pirate Bay co-founder Fredrik Neij released from prison|work=Ars Technica}}</ref><ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20170103092941/http://www.aftonbladet.se/senastenytt/ttnyheter/inrikes/article20900279.ab</ref>
